title: For Sale:  Marlin 30-30 model 93 in excellent condition
postcontent:
barrel stamped The Marlin Firearms Corporation special smokeless steel serial # 119? the gun is in excellent shape. looking to sale or trade
call or text REDACTED asking $750 obo..also open to trades
info on gun... After WWI the newly formed Marlin Firearms Corporation started the serial numbers all over again. If your gun's barrel is marked, "Marlin Firearms Corporation" it is made in the mid to late 1920's. If it is marked, "Marlin Firearms Co." it was made in the early 1920's. If it has this same Marlin Firearms Co. marking on the barrel, but also has the "bullseye" in the buttstock, it is post1924-1930 era. All Marlins marked "Model '93" on the top tang were made after WWI. The catalogs designated the change from 1893 to '93 in around 1905, but too many receivers with the early marking were already made up, so the new stamped 93 after WWI

For sale is a complete Smith & Wesson M&P-9 Competition Set. This set was intended to be a back-up set for my primary IPSC/USPSA competition gun, but never got used. I got about 100 rounds through the gun to test the lightened trigger, sight it in, and play around with it for a bit. It ran flawlessly with stock ammo. It was cleaned right after and placed in the safe where it has just been sitting. So now I decided to let it go and see if I can fund another project.

The gun is an M&P9 full-size 9mm with a 4.25” barrel, average market price of about $600. I’ve had it for less than a year and it’s practically brand new. Just to give you an idea on how new this gun is; the envelope that has the casing from the test fire at the factory is dated 02/20/2012. The gun originally came with Trijicon Nightsights which were replaced with Novak fiber optic front sight and Novak rear sight that are the same as what comes with the M&P Pro model. The gun also came originally with the magazine disconnect safety which has been removed. The trigger has been modified and now has a smooth trigger pull with a crisp break at 4¼ pounds and a short reset. These modifications cost me $180 in parts and labor. The gun is very clean with no scuff marks except minor ones on the Novak sights when they were installed. 

Everything that the gun came with originally will be sent along with it: 
• Original case
• 2 factory 17-round magazines
• Original Trijicon nightsights set
• Original Mag Safety Parts
• 3 interchangeable Palmswell grips
• Plastic chamber safety plug

• 3 additional factory 17-round magazines that are brand new and have never been used (Current market value of $50 each if you can find them)

• 2 BladeTech double mag pouch with Tek-Lok and modified with spacers to offset for easier draw, still brand new. (value of $55 each)

This is a ready-to-go competition set. All you need is ammo and you’re good to go. I have about $1110 total and a lot of time put in into completing this set. I’m selling the complete set for $950. title: For Sale:  AK-47 GP-WASR 10/63 Rifle, Extra Mags & Ammo AK47
postcontent: Century’s version of the standard-bearer AKM is the GP WASR-10. The 7.62×39 mm rifle is manufactured at the Cugir factory in Romania, a country that is one of the world’s more prominent manufacturers and suppliers of AK-style rifles. It is imported into this country by Century where it is modified and fitted with U.S. parts for BATFE compliance. Fit and finish of the 8-pound, 5-ounce Parkerized rifle clearly reflects the philosophy behind the design—utilitarian and nothing more. The high-capacity magazines lock solidly and easily into place on this AK variant. Its 161/4-inch barrel even exhibits exterior tooling marks, and parts such as the front and rear sight bases and gas port block have rough shaping impressions. The GP WASR-10 does a good job of mimicking a true AKM rifle and all its requisite updates from the original AK-47 design. Like the AKM rifle, it has a stamped receiver and a ribbed top cover. The fixed stock is also reminiscent of an AKM, as it is made from laminated wood. As of 2008, there are GP WASR-10/63 rifles which are being made from demilled military rifles. Look for a triangle with arrow on the front trunnion. Quality is much better with these.This rifle and all accessories are new and have never been fire. I understand there are “MARKS” on the receiver. These are not wear marks and were obtained by other firearms touching the parkerized finish while in a safe.

title: For Sale/Trade:  LNiB Vepr Ak47
postcontent:
Up for sale I have a a like new in box Vepr AK47. This gun is beautiful and in like new condition with a thumbhole woodpattern poly stock. To my knowledge the only scratches that are on it are where the safety and the gas valve levers drag. I traded for this recently, but have changed my armoury goals to concealed carry necessities and accessories for myself and my wife, so after putting an estimated 20 rounds through it, it is for sale.

This is widely considered one of the most accurate AKs out there and it has an integrated siderail for optic mounting. Its receiver is estimated to be at least 50% stronger than the average ak receiver because it is based upon the RPK submachine gun receiver.

This gun comes with a 5 round hunting magazine and a cleaning kit. The design was made to be imported during the original assault weapons ban in America, so it requires a small modification to get it to accept regular AK mags. This really isn't a big deal and I would do it if I were planning on keeping it. There are 20 and 30 round mags out there designed for it specifically, so it is good to go stock if you wanted to keep it simple.

Call or text me at 901 tew fyve ate 1520.

title: For Sale:  Mauser K98 Russian Capture (with scope rings)
postcontent:
I have a K98 Mauser 8mm (stamped 1944). This particular model is a czech manufactured rifle with Nazi proof marks. The eagle still remains on the various parts. The swastika has been removed as this was a Russian Capture. It was imported by Century in what I believe to be the 90s when they brought a few of these in. 

The rifle is military surplus and therefore has normal wear and tear for a surplus rifle. The rifle still shoots and is accurate, the bore is immaculate. I was planning on using this as a hunting rifle, but will not be hunting this year. 

Included are the scope rings (the receiver has been drilled) These are reproduction rings that fetch over $150 from the manufactures. The are the high turret sniper style and the iron sights can be viewed with the scope mounted to the rifle. The rifle also has the large rotating safety (reproduction) used on the sniper rifles. The safety is either fire, or on safe with the ability to open the bolt. The traditional mauser "locked bolt safety" is still possible with the bolt, but not with this safety. 

Not all parts are matching, as it was a russian capture that was re-arsenal. All parts are the rebuild were matched with electro pencil by the russians (most likely down in Yugoslavia) THIS IS NOT A YUGO Mauser, and all parts have the original German proofs. 

Also includes Redfield steel tube scope (TV box style) 6x zoom (non adjustable)

Also includes 15 round of M75 8mm surplus ammo.

Here is your chance to own a fairly cheap Mauser rifle with some history. The 1944 M44 Mosin nagant also pictured is for sale, it is an izhevsk manufactured.
